      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "What is an Azure AD tenant?",
      "pos": [
        574,
        601
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In the physical workplace, the word tenant can be defined as a group or company that occupies a building.",
      "pos": [
        603,
        708
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For instance, your organization may own office space in a building.",
      "pos": [
        709,
        776
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This building may be on a street with several other organizations.",
      "pos": [
        777,
        843
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Your organization would be considered a tenant of that building.",
      "pos": [
        844,
        908
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This building is an asset of your organization and provides security and ensures that you can conduct business safely.",
      "pos": [
        909,
        1027
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It also is separated from the other businesses on your street.",
      "pos": [
        1028,
        1090
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This ensures that your organization and the assets therein are isolated from other organizations.",
      "pos": [
        1091,
        1188
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In the cloud-enabled workplace, a tenant can be defined as a client or organization that owns and manages a specific instance of that cloud service.",
      "pos": [
        1190,
        1338
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "With the identity platform provided by Microsoft Azure, a tenant is simply a dedicated instance of Azure Active Directory (Azure AD) that your organization receives and owns when it signs up for a Microsoft cloud service such as Azure or Office 365.",
      "pos": [
        1339,
        1588
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Each Azure AD directory is distinct and separate from other Azure AD directories.",
      "pos": [
        1590,
        1671
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Just like a corporate office building is a secure asset specific to only your organization, an Azure AD directory was also designed to be a secure asset for use by only your organization.",
      "pos": [
        1672,
        1859
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The Azure AD architecture isolates customer data and identity information from co-mingling.",
      "pos": [
        1860,
        1951
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This means that users and administrators of one Azure AD directory cannot accidentally or maliciously access data in another directory.",
      "pos": [
        1952,
        2087
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "![][1]",
      "pos": [
        2089,
        2095
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "How can I get an Azure AD directory?",
      "pos": [
        2100,
        2136
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure AD provides the core directory and identity management capabilities behind most of Microsoft’s cloud services, including:",
      "pos": [
        2138,
        2265
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure",
      "pos": [
        2269,
        2274
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Microsoft Office 365",
      "pos": [
        2277,
        2297
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Microsoft Dynamics CRM Online",
      "pos": [
        2300,
        2329
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Microsoft Intune",
      "pos": [
        2332,
        2348
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You will get an Azure AD directory when you sign up for any of these Microsoft cloud services.",
      "pos": [
        2350,
        2444
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can create additional directories as needed.",
      "pos": [
        2445,
        2493
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, you might maintain your first directory as a production directory and then create another directory for testing or staging.",
      "pos": [
        2494,
        2630
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        2634,
        2834
      ],
      "content": "[AZURE.NOTE]\nAfter you sign up for your first service, we recommend that you use the same administrator account associated with your organization when you sign up for other Microsoft cloud services.",
      "leadings": [
        "",
        "> "
      ],
      "nodes": [
        {
          "content": "After you sign up for your first service, we recommend that you use the same administrator account associated with your organization when you sign up for other Microsoft cloud services.",
          "pos": [
            13,
            198
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The first time you sign up for a Microsoft cloud service, you are prompted to provide details about your organization and your organization’s Internet domain name registration.",
      "pos": [
        2836,
        3012
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This information is then used to create a new Azure AD directory instance for your organization.",
      "pos": [
        3013,
        3109
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "That same directory is used to authenticate sign in attempts when you subscribe to multiple Microsoft cloud services.",
      "pos": [
        3110,
        3227
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The additional services fully leverage any existing user accounts, policies, settings or on-premises directory integration you configure to help improve efficiency between your organization’s identity infrastructure on-premises and Azure AD.",
      "pos": [
        3229,
        3470
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, if you originally signed up for a Microsoft Intune subscription and completed the steps necessary to further integrate your on-premises Active Directory with your Azure AD directory by deploying directory synchronization and/or single sign-on servers, you can sign up for another Microsoft cloud service such as Office 365 which can also leverage the same directory integration benefits you now use with Microsoft Intune.",
      "pos": [
        3472,
        3906
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        3908,
        4049
      ],
      "content": "For more information about integrating your on-premises directory with Azure AD, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Directory integration<ept id=\"p1\">](active-directory-aadconnect.md)</ept>."
    },
    {
      "content": "Associate an Azure AD directory with a new Azure subscription",
      "pos": [
        4055,
        4116
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can associate a new Azure subscription with the same directory that authenticates sign in for an existing Office 365 or Microsoft Intune subscription.",
      "pos": [
        4118,
        4272
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Sign in to the Azure Management Portal using your work or school account.",
      "pos": [
        4273,
        4346
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The Management Portal returns a message that it was unable to find any subscriptions for that account.",
      "pos": [
        4347,
        4449
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Select <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Sign Up For Azure<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, and your directory will be available for administration within the portal.",
      "pos": [
        4450,
        4554
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Manage the directory for your Office 365 subscription in Azure<ept id=\"p1\">](active-directory-how-subscriptions-associated-directory.md#manage-the-directory-for-your-office-365-subscription-in-azure)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        4555,
        4769
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        4771,
        4997
      ],
      "content": "For a video about common usage questions for Azure AD, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Azure Active Directory - Common Sign-up, sign-in and usage questions<ept id=\"p1\">](http://channel9.msdn.com/Series/Windows-Azure-Active-Directory/WAADCommonSignupsigninquestions)</ept>."
    },
    {
      "content": "Create an Azure AD directory by signing up for a Microsoft cloud service as an organization",
      "pos": [
        5003,
