    {
      "content": "Manage an Azure-provisioned Default directory",
      "pos": [
        5593,
        5638
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Today, a directory is automatically created when you sign up for Azure and your subscription is associated with that directory.",
      "pos": [
        5640,
        5767
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "But if you originally signed up for Azure before October 2013, a directory was not automatically created.",
      "pos": [
        5768,
        5873
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In that case, Azure may have “backfilled” for your account by provisioning a Default directory for it.",
      "pos": [
        5874,
        5976
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Your subscription was then associated with that Default directory.",
      "pos": [
        5977,
        6043
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Backfilling of directories was done in October 2013 as part of an overall improvement to the security model for Azure.",
      "pos": [
        6045,
        6163
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It helps offer organizational identity features to all Azure customers and ensures that all Azure resources are accessed in the context of a user in directory.",
      "pos": [
        6164,
        6323
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You cannot use Azure without a directory.",
      "pos": [
        6324,
        6365
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To achieve that, any user who was signed up prior to July 7, 2013 but did not have a directory had to have one created.",
      "pos": [
        6366,
        6485
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you had already created a directory, then your subscription was associated with that directory.",
      "pos": [
        6486,
        6584
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There are no costs for using Azure AD.",
      "pos": [
        6586,
        6624
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The directory is a free resource.",
      "pos": [
        6625,
        6658
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There is an additional Azure Active Directory Premium tier that is licensed separately and provides additional features such as company branding and self-service password reset.",
      "pos": [
        6659,
        6836
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To change the display name of your directory, click the directory in the portal and click <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Configure<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        6838,
        6942
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "As explained later in this topic, you can add a new directory or delete a directory that you no longer need.",
      "pos": [
        6943,
        7051
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To associate your subscription with a different directory, click the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Settings<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> extension in the left navigation, and at the bottom of the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Subscriptions<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> page, click <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>Edit Directory<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        7052,
        7242
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can also create a custom domain using a DNS name that you have registered instead of the default *.onmicrosoft.com domain, which may be preferable with a service such as SharePoint Online.",
      "pos": [
        7243,
        7435
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "How can I manage directory data",
      "pos": [
        7440,
        7471
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "As an administrator of one or more Microsoft cloud service subscriptions, you can either use the Azure Management Portal, the Microsoft Intune account portal, or the Office 365 Admin Center to manage your organizations directory data.",
      "pos": [
        7473,
        7707
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can also download and run <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Microsoft Azure Active Directory Module for Windows PowerShell<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/azure/jj151815.aspx)</ept> cmdlets to help you manage data stored in Azure AD.",
      "pos": [
        7708,
        7910
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "From either of these portals (or cmdlets), you can:",
      "pos": [
        7912,
        7963
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Create and manage user and group accounts",
      "pos": [
        7967,
        8008
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Manage related cloud service(s) your organization subscribes to",
      "pos": [
        8011,
        8074
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Set up on-premises integration with your directory service",
      "pos": [
        8077,
        8135
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The Azure Management Portal, Office 365 Admin Center, Microsoft Intune account portal and the Azure AD cmdlets all read from and write to a single shared instance of Azure AD that is associated with your organization’s directory, as shown in the following illustration.",
      "pos": [
        8137,
        8406
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In this way, portals (or cmdlets) act as a front-end interface that pull in and/or modify your directory data.",
      "pos": [
        8407,
        8517
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "![][2]",
      "pos": [
        8519,
        8525
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "These account portals and the associated Azure AD PowerShell cmdlets used to manage users and groups are built on top of the Azure AD platform.",
      "pos": [
        8527,
        8670
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When you make a change to your organizations data using any of the portals (or cmdlets) while signed in under the context of one of these services, the change will also be shown in the other portals the next time you sign-in under the context of that service because this data is shared across the Microsoft cloud services you are subscribed to.",
      "pos": [
        8672,
        9017
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, if you used the Office 365 Admin Center to block a user from signing in, that action will block the user from signing in to any other service that your organization is currently subscribed to.",
      "pos": [
        9018,
        9223
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you were to pull up that same user’s account under the context of the Microsoft Intune account portal you will see that the user is blocked.",
      "pos": [
        9224,
        9367
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "How can I add and manage multiple directories?",
      "pos": [
        9372,
        9418
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can add an Azure AD directory in the Azure Management Portal.",
      "pos": [
        9420,
        9485
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Select the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Active Directory<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> extension on the left and click <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Add<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        9486,
        9558
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can manage each directory as a fully independent resource: each directory is a peer, fully-featured, and logically independent of other directories that you manage; there is no parent-child relationship between directories.",
      "pos": [
        9560,
        9787
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This independence between directories includes resource independence, administrative independence, and synchronization independence.",
      "pos": [
        9788,
        9920
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Resource independence<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        9924,
        9950
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you create or delete a resource in one directory, it has no impact on any resource in another directory, with the partial exception of external users, described below.",
      "pos": [
        9951,
        10121
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you use a custom domain 'contoso.com' with one directory, it cannot be used with any other directory.",
      "pos": [
        10122,
        10226
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Administrative independence<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        10229,
        10261
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If a non-administrative user of directory 'Contoso', creates a test directory 'Test' then:",
      "pos": [
        10263,
        10353
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "◦The directory sync tool, to synchronize data with a single AD forest.",
      "pos": [
        10360,
        10430
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "◦The administrators of directory 'Contoso' have no direct administrative privileges to directory 'Test' unless an administrator of 'Test' specifically grants them these privileges.",
      "pos": [
        10437,
        10617
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Administrators of 'Contoso' can control access to directory 'Test' by virtue of their control of the user account which created 'Test.'",
      "pos": [
        10618,
        10753
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "And if you change (add or remove) an administrator role for a user in one directory, the change does not affect any administrator role that user may have in another directory.",
      "pos": [
        10759,
        10934
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Synchronization independence<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        10939,
        10972
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can configure each Azure AD independently to get data synchronized from a single instance of either:",
      "pos": [
        10973,
        11077
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The directory sync tool, to synchronize data with a single AD forest",
      "pos": [
        11084,
        11152
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The Azure Active Directory Connector for Forefront Identity Manager, to synchronize data with one or more on-premises forests, and/or non-AD data sources.",
      "pos": [
        11159,
        11313
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Also note that unlike other Azure resources, your directories are not child resources of an Azure subscription.",
      "pos": [
        11315,
        11426
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "So if you cancel or allow your Azure subscription to expire, you can still access your directory data using Azure AD PowerShell, the Azure Graph API, or other interfaces such as the Office 365 Admin Center.",
      "pos": [
        11427,
        11633
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can also associate another subscription with the directory.",
      "pos": [
        11634,
        11697
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "How can I delete an Azure AD directory?",
      "pos": [
        11702,
        11741
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A global administrator can delete an Azure AD directory from the portal.",
      "pos": [
        11742,
        11814
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When a directory is deleted, all resources contained in the directory are also deleted; so you should be sure you don’t need the directory before you delete it.",
